Limitation of Solar Power is we have Certain Hours of Sunlight to Power our Infracture. Therefore it will not be possible to completely switch to Solar Energy.¶

Renuable_India_PowerPlants = IndiaPowerPlants[IndiaPowerPlants.primary_fuel.isin(['Solar', 'Wind', 'Hydro', 'Biomass'])]
filtered_data = Renuable_India_PowerPlants[['latitude', 'longitude', 'primary_fuel']]
unique_fuels = filtered_data['primary_fuel'].unique()
fuel_colors = {'Solar':'orange', 'Wind':'green', 'Hydro':'blue', 'Biomass':'brown'}
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))

for fuel in unique_fuels:
    fuel_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['primary_fuel'] == fuel]
    color = fuel_colors[fuel]
    plt.scatter(
        fuel_data['longitude'],
        fuel_data['latitude'],
        marker='o',
        s=5,
        alpha=1,
        color=color,
        label=fuel
    )

plt.title('Power Plant Locations in India based on Green Energy')
plt.xlabel('Longitude')
plt.ylabel('Latitude')
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()
The chart provided illustrates the presence of power plants using different energy sources, specifically Hydro, Wind, Solar, and Biomass. However, it's important to understand the dynamic relationship between these energy sources.¶
Hydro power plants are known for their ability to store water below a reservoir during periods of excess energy production, often during the daytime. This stored water represents potential energy that can be converted into kinetic energy when needed.¶
To optimize the utilization of this potential energy, Wind, Solar, and Biomass power sources play a crucial role. During the daytime, when energy production from these sources is abundant, they can collectively power the Hydro project. This surplus energy can be used to pump water back to the top of the reservoir, effectively converting kinetic energy into potential energy. This process essentially "recharges" the Hydro project, making it ready to generate electricity during periods of high demand, such as at night.¶

filtered_data = IndiaPowerPlants[['latitude', 'longitude', 'primary_fuel']]

unique_fuels = filtered_data['primary_fuel'].unique()

unique_fuels = [
    'Wind',
    'Solar',
    'Hydro',
    'Biomass',
    'Geothermal',
    'Wave and Tidal',
    'Nuclear',
    'Gas',
    'Storage',
    'Cogeneration',
    'Waste',
    'Other',
    'Oil',
    'Coal',
    'Petcoke'
]

# Generate a colormap that transitions from green to red
n = len(unique_fuels)
colors = [(i/n, 1-i/n, 0) for i in range(n)]
cmap = mcolors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('green_to_red', colors, N=n)

# Assign colors to each fuel
fuel_colors = {fuel: cmap(i/n) for i, fuel in enumerate(unique_fuels)}

# Create a scatter plot with random colors for each fuel type
# plt.figure(figsize=(18, 8))
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))

for fuel in unique_fuels:
    fuel_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['primary_fuel'] == fuel]
    color = fuel_colors[fuel]
    plt.scatter(
        fuel_data['longitude'],
        fuel_data['latitude'],
        marker='o',
        s=5,
        alpha=1,
        color=color,
        label=fuel
    )

plt.title('Power Plant Locations in India based on Green Energy to Not Green Energy')
plt.xlabel('Longitude')
plt.ylabel('Latitude')
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Based on above data India has lots of Renewable Energy with Very Less Non Renewable Energy Power Plants But Power is generated more from Non Renewable sources.¶

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 8))

# First Pie Chart - Distribution of Power Plants by Count
PowerPlantCount = GlobalPowerPlantDataset.groupby('primary_fuel').count()['name of powerplant'].reset_index().sort_values('name of powerplant', ascending=False)
axes[0].pie(PowerPlantCount['name of powerplant'], labels=PowerPlantCount['primary_fuel'], autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=0)
axes[0].set_title("Distribution of Power Plants by Primary Fuel (Count)")
axes[0].axis('equal')  

# Second Pie Chart - Distribution of Power Plants by Capacity
PowerPlantCapacity = GlobalPowerPlantDataset.groupby('primary_fuel').sum()['capacity in MW'].reset_index().sort_values('capacity in MW', ascending=False)
axes[1].pie(PowerPlantCapacity['capacity in MW'], labels=PowerPlantCapacity['primary_fuel'], autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=0)
axes[1].set_title("Distribution of Power Plants by Primary Fuel (Capacity)")
axes[1].axis('equal') 

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Plots to Understand PowerPlant and the MW Capacity Across Globe¶

In [71]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Get unique primary fuel types
unique_fuels = GlobalPowerPlantDataset['primary_fuel'].unique()

# Create a figure with subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(len(unique_fuels), 1 , figsize=(18, 40))

# Loop through each unique primary fuel type
for i, fuel in enumerate(unique_fuels):
    # Filter the data for power plants with the current primary fuel and sort by capacity in MW
    fuel_data = GlobalPowerPlantDataset[GlobalPowerPlantDataset['primary_fuel'] == fuel].sort_values('capacity in MW', ascending=False)
    
    # Create a horizontal line plot for the current primary fuel
    axes[i].plot(range(1, len(fuel_data) + 1), fuel_data['capacity in MW'], marker='o', linestyle='-')
    axes[i].set_title(f"Capacity of {fuel} Power Plants (Descending Order)")
    axes[i].set_xlabel("Capacity (MW)")
    axes[i].set_ylabel("Power Plant Index")

# Adjust the layout
plt.tight_layout()

# Show the plots
plt.show()

In [ ]:
all_info = []
for i in range(1,100):
    print(i)
    driver.get(f'https://www.accuweather.com/en/in/ahmednagar/2749633/daily-weather-forecast/2749633?day={i}')
    soup1 = BeautifulSoup(driver.page_source, 'html.parser')
    weather_elements = soup1.find_all('div', 'half-day-card-content')
    date = soup1.find('div','subnav-pagination').text.replace('\n','')
    for soup in weather_elements:
        data_dict = {}
        data_dict['day'] = i
        data_dict['date'] = date
        ptag = soup.find_all('p')
        for item in ptag:
            key = item.text.split('span')[0].strip() 
            value = item.find('span', class_='value').text.strip()
            key = key.replace(value,'')
            data_dict[key] = value
        all_info.append(data_dict)
